      <text><![CDATA[<p> Let \( \log_ab = {@N@}\) and \( \log_ac = {@M@}\). Express \( \log_a(bc) \) in terms of 
\({@N@}\) and \({@M@}\). </p>
<p> \( \log_a(bc) \) = [[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]] </p>]]></text>
    </questiontext>
    <generalfeedback format="html">
      <text><![CDATA[<p> Since \({@N@} = \log_ab\), \(b = a^{{@N@}}\). Similarly, \({@M@} = \log_ac\) implies \(c = a^{{@M@}}\).</p>
<p>Hence, \(bc = a^{{@N@}}a^{{@M@}} = a^{{@N@}+{@M@}}\), which implies \(\log_a(bc) = {@N@}+{@M@}\).</p>
<p>Therefore, using the property of indices, we have shown that 
\[\log_a(bc)={@N@}+{@M@}=\log_ab+\log_ac.\] </p>]]></text>
    </generalfeedback>
